410
01:49:43,032 --> 01:49:54,901
[SPEAKER_03]: Moving on to the next slide, here what I'd like to talk about is what we've done so far for studying the heating and air conditioning and ventilation options.

411
01:49:55,961 --> 01:50:02,126
[SPEAKER_03]: In particular, what we bring to table as far as the thermal energy sources.

412
01:50:02,946 --> 01:50:06,029
[SPEAKER_03]: So in light of the electrification,

413
01:50:07,450 --> 01:50:13,802
[SPEAKER_03]: We've looked at three different options and we're presenting to you what we've evaluated so far.

414
01:50:15,944 --> 01:50:29,154
[SPEAKER_03]: Generally, heat pumps use, they're all electric systems, and they use different sources to extract heat from a particular source, whether it be an air or ground source.

415
01:50:29,434 --> 01:50:31,396
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's what we're presenting.

416
01:50:31,416 --> 01:50:32,336
[SPEAKER_03]: So we have three options.

417
01:50:32,436 --> 01:50:43,525
[SPEAKER_03]: Option one is the air to water source heat pump, where the heat pumps are utilizing air to draw heat in and out of the building.

418
01:50:45,563 --> 01:50:47,315
[SPEAKER_03]: You can think of the heat pump as a...

419
01:50:48,886 --> 01:50:52,209
[SPEAKER_03]: And in simple terms, it's kind of like a refrigerator in a house.

420
01:50:52,930 --> 01:50:59,095
[SPEAKER_03]: So a house being the outside and the refrigerator being the actual conditioned space that it's serving.

421
01:50:59,915 --> 01:51:03,358
[SPEAKER_03]: The only difference between that and this is the scale of things.

422
01:51:04,239 --> 01:51:07,442
[SPEAKER_03]: And what heat pumps do is they're also reversing.

423
01:51:07,522 --> 01:51:13,567
[SPEAKER_03]: So in a technology, they can provide heating and cooling and sometimes simultaneous heating and cooling too.

424
01:51:13,887 --> 01:51:16,910
[SPEAKER_03]: So technology has evolved a lot when it comes to heat pumps.

425
01:51:18,510 --> 01:51:21,132
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'll go a little more in detail in the next few slides.

426
01:51:21,332 --> 01:51:32,943
[SPEAKER_03]: The option two that we've studied is a ground source or also called geothermal option where the source of energy is essentially earth.

427
01:51:33,363 --> 01:51:44,533
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, heat sink is used to take the heat out of the building in summer months and putting into the earth and then draw back in winter months to heat the building.

428
01:51:45,632 --> 01:51:49,995
[SPEAKER_03]: The third option that we are looking at is air source heat pump options.

429
01:51:50,015 --> 01:51:57,240
[SPEAKER_03]: This is sort of a hybrid option where we look at the VRF systems combined with air to water source heat pump for reheat.

430
01:51:57,600 --> 01:52:00,622
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll get into that a little more detail shortly here.

431
01:52:02,144 --> 01:52:07,147
[SPEAKER_03]: Each of these options reduce energy use and also lowers emissions.

432
01:52:12,369 --> 01:52:15,331
[SPEAKER_03]: The options vary in cost, complexity, and incentives.

433
01:52:15,411 --> 01:52:21,855
[SPEAKER_03]: So each one of them have pros and cons in what they bring to the table.

434
01:52:22,896 --> 01:52:26,178
[SPEAKER_03]: Next slide is option one, air to water source heat pumps.

435
01:52:26,218 --> 01:52:40,927
[SPEAKER_03]: So like I described earlier, in this particular option, the air to water source heat pumps are going to be located inside the well and are going to be used to provide heating and cooling.

436
01:52:42,998 --> 01:52:55,205
[SPEAKER_03]: They have an inherent problem, not problem, limitation where they stop operating at a certain ambient conditions, so require a backup source, which would be boilers.

437
01:52:56,645 --> 01:53:01,728
[SPEAKER_03]: And the boilers will only be used as a backup when the temperatures go sub-zero.

438
01:53:05,093 --> 01:53:11,376
[SPEAKER_03]: In this option, what we intend to do is the existing air handling units, we like to replace certain things.

439
01:53:11,476 --> 01:53:16,819
[SPEAKER_03]: For example, all of these existing air handling units have refrigerant coils in them.

440
01:53:17,859 --> 01:53:21,501
[SPEAKER_03]: Those will be replaced with hot water, chill water coils.

441
01:53:23,706 --> 01:53:32,875
[SPEAKER_03]: And we're going to modify controls, add controls to the air handling units for better modularity and efficiency.

442
01:53:33,255 --> 01:53:39,641
[SPEAKER_03]: So currently out of the three air handling units, one is a variable air volume system, while the others are constant.

443
01:53:40,242 --> 01:53:44,446
[SPEAKER_03]: And with constant means the fan's running all the time, using a lot more energy.

444
01:53:44,466 --> 01:53:48,690
[SPEAKER_03]: So introducing intelligent controls will help save us energy.

445
01:53:50,493 --> 01:54:07,582
[SPEAKER_03]: All the terminal units that are inside the building will be replaced with new, primarily because they're all designed for higher water temperature associated with boilers, whereas heat pump technology provides lower water temperatures.

446
01:54:08,122 --> 01:54:14,145
[SPEAKER_03]: So everything needs to be replaced with kind, however, sized for appropriate water temperature.

447
01:54:16,542 --> 01:54:20,631
[SPEAKER_03]: The, any questions so far on this air to water source heat pump?

448
01:54:21,633 --> 01:54:21,834
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

449
01:54:22,976 --> 01:54:25,883
[SPEAKER_03]: Next option is the geothermal ground source heat pump option.

450
01:54:28,814 --> 01:54:31,275
[SPEAKER_03]: The thermal source is essentially geothermal wells.

451
01:54:31,695 --> 01:54:35,536
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a slide coming that kind of shows, you know, how the wells are laid out.

452
01:54:37,077 --> 01:54:46,641
[SPEAKER_03]: And this, the difference between this and the previous option is that all the equipment is indoors.

453
01:54:47,261 --> 01:54:54,103
[SPEAKER_03]: So the heat pumps actually reside inside mechanical room which is the current mechanical room have enough space to accommodate them.

454
01:54:54,143 --> 01:54:55,324
[SPEAKER_03]: That's where we think they would go.

455
01:54:56,253 --> 01:55:00,194
[SPEAKER_03]: And so we don't think that there's additional mechanical room requirements for that.

456
01:55:01,414 --> 01:55:09,116
[SPEAKER_03]: What happens is that there are pumps that pump water from geothermal field to the mechanical room.

457
01:55:10,056 --> 01:55:11,257
[SPEAKER_03]: It goes through the heat pump.

458
01:55:11,277 --> 01:55:13,957
[SPEAKER_03]: That's where the conversion happens.

459
01:55:14,057 --> 01:55:17,518
[SPEAKER_03]: That's where you reject and absorb the heat.

460
01:55:18,166 --> 01:55:23,191
[SPEAKER_03]: And then you would use additional set of pumps for heating and cooling and supply to the building.

461
01:55:23,851 --> 01:55:29,817
[SPEAKER_03]: And that would mean replacing any refrigerant coils in the air handling unit system.

462
01:55:29,877 --> 01:55:37,585
[SPEAKER_03]: So essentially what we do with the air handling unit systems in the previous option, this is the same except that, you know, the source is different.

463
01:55:38,695 --> 01:55:41,196
[SPEAKER_03]: Same goes for terminal heating devices, same thing.

464
01:55:42,796 --> 01:55:48,278
[SPEAKER_03]: The water temperatures are much not as hot as the boiler system.

465
01:55:48,318 --> 01:55:53,719
[SPEAKER_03]: So you're talking about 120 to 130 degree water versus 180 plus minus.

466
01:55:53,779 --> 01:55:59,881
[SPEAKER_03]: So it requires all the terminal heat devices to be changed.

467
01:55:59,901 --> 01:56:07,603
[SPEAKER_03]: That includes VAV boxes, cabin unit heaters, propeller unit heaters, and your unit ventilators.

468
01:56:08,710 --> 01:56:11,155
[SPEAKER_03]: or any perimeter fin tube, stuff like that.

469
01:56:13,300 --> 01:56:15,084
[SPEAKER_03]: Will you go on to the next slide, please?

