512
02:01:36,733 --> 02:01:42,936
[SPEAKER_21]: So it just reduces the space needed for those air handlers to about 9,000 square feet.

513
02:01:44,377 --> 02:01:48,778
[SPEAKER_21]: But it still leaves plenty of room for getting some renewable energy onto the site.

514
02:01:49,018 --> 02:01:54,421
[SPEAKER_21]: Can you go to the next slide, please?

515
02:01:57,302 --> 02:01:59,763
[SPEAKER_17]: So I think the important

516
02:02:00,493 --> 02:02:03,994
[SPEAKER_17]: point here on the three options is what do they cost?

517
02:02:04,254 --> 02:02:08,714
[SPEAKER_17]: So we'll be presenting the life cycle cost analysis that we did.

518
02:02:08,814 --> 02:02:12,295
[SPEAKER_17]: So in order to do this, we build a computer model of the building.

519
02:02:13,095 --> 02:02:20,936
[SPEAKER_17]: We declare what system options are going to be, the insulation, hours of operations.

520
02:02:21,457 --> 02:02:30,098
[SPEAKER_17]: A lot of these things are assumptions at this time, but it's been set up so it's equal on all three options and we can do a comparison.

521
02:02:32,310 --> 02:02:42,218
[SPEAKER_17]: So this shows the capital cost of just the HVAC systems on the left column there.

522
02:02:42,899 --> 02:02:49,765
[SPEAKER_17]: So you can see that the cheapest capital, the least capital cost is the air to water heat pump system.

523
02:02:51,967 --> 02:03:06,754
[SPEAKER_17]: This may be a little counterintuitive if you've seen air source heat pump on other projects, but it has to do with the nuances of this project, specifically that we are removing the unit ventilators.

524
02:03:06,774 --> 02:03:13,457
[SPEAKER_17]: The unit ventilators, as Goshi mentioned, not only they poke through the exterior wall,

525
02:03:14,546 --> 02:03:19,869
[SPEAKER_17]: in order to air condition the space, but also for the ventilation.

526
02:03:20,290 --> 02:03:30,015
[SPEAKER_17]: So if we remove those, we have to add back in ventilation, which is the dedicated outdoor energy recovery unit that Goshi mentioned.

527
02:03:30,035 --> 02:03:40,762
[SPEAKER_17]: So that is why that the capital costs of option three are a bit higher, and the costs of

528
02:03:41,803 --> 02:03:48,026
[SPEAKER_17]: The option two, the ground source heat pump, that differential comes mostly from the drilling that is required.

529
02:03:48,847 --> 02:03:58,371
[SPEAKER_17]: So the middle column shows the total project costs, and then the far right shows the differential.

530
02:04:00,773 --> 02:04:11,378
[SPEAKER_17]: If we move to the next slide, what you'll see here are incentives, so tax credits and mass save that can help to offset some of these costs.

531
02:04:12,367 --> 02:04:16,368
[SPEAKER_17]: Mass Save provides incentives for all heat pump projects.

532
02:04:17,109 --> 02:04:20,830
[SPEAKER_17]: So we've put those in the far right column.

533
02:04:21,230 --> 02:04:25,612
[SPEAKER_17]: You get slightly higher incentive for the ground source heat pumps.

534
02:04:26,292 --> 02:04:40,117
[SPEAKER_17]: The other benefit of the ground source heat pumps is the tax credits we've worked with a company to help estimate what tax credits might be available for this project.

535
02:04:40,853 --> 02:04:48,857
[SPEAKER_17]: It's important to understand that these are a snapshot of the incentives and tax credits at this point in time.

536
02:04:49,017 --> 02:04:53,579
[SPEAKER_17]: These are ever-changing and not guaranteed.

537
02:04:55,940 --> 02:05:07,806
[SPEAKER_17]: So if we move to the next slide, I think that this is an important slide to show the difference in performance for the building as it currently stands.

538
02:05:09,759 --> 02:05:12,423
[SPEAKER_17]: in comparison to what we are proposing.

539
02:05:12,984 --> 02:05:16,368
[SPEAKER_17]: So what this slide is showing is energy use intensity.

540
02:05:16,849 --> 02:05:18,591
[SPEAKER_17]: So that is how much energy in

541
02:05:20,948 --> 02:05:23,250
[SPEAKER_17]: KBTU per square foot per year.

542
02:05:23,851 --> 02:05:26,813
[SPEAKER_17]: And this equalizes across systems.

543
02:05:27,073 --> 02:05:34,279
[SPEAKER_17]: So it does not consider the source of the energy.

544
02:05:34,419 --> 02:05:44,887
[SPEAKER_17]: So the source may be a coal-fired plant providing electricity, it might be a hydroelectric dam providing electricity, or it might be on-site combustion.

545
02:05:45,795 --> 02:05:51,338
