815
02:31:47,767 --> 02:31:51,628
[SPEAKER_22]: Non-engineer answer, then I'll let you take it.

816
02:31:52,109 --> 02:31:53,809
[SPEAKER_22]: So it's a water-based system.

817
02:31:54,129 --> 02:32:00,392
[SPEAKER_22]: So it's essentially what you have for the educational areas now.

818
02:32:01,172 --> 02:32:03,453
[SPEAKER_22]: So it's a fairly simple system to operate.

819
02:32:04,373 --> 02:32:11,315
[SPEAKER_22]: The third option, which uses refrigeration and cassettes, there's a lot of different types.

820
02:32:11,415 --> 02:32:14,897
[SPEAKER_22]: So what we'd end up, like different areas, we need different solutions.

821
02:32:15,777 --> 02:32:23,908
[SPEAKER_22]: you end up adding a lot of technical challenges instead of a singular type system that's sort of unified across the building.

822
02:32:24,269 --> 02:32:26,051
[SPEAKER_22]: That's my non-engineering answer.

823
02:32:26,091 --> 02:32:26,472
[SPEAKER_22]: How did I do?

824
02:32:27,603 --> 02:32:29,945
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll piggyback on what Brian said.

825
02:32:30,005 --> 02:32:41,714
[SPEAKER_03]: So essentially, in modern electrification, especially today, we look for what's the most efficient and most appropriate systems for certain types of buildings.

826
02:32:41,754 --> 02:32:49,140
[SPEAKER_03]: And in commercial industrial buildings today, we see that ground source heat pump is the most efficient because of the coefficient of power.

827
02:32:49,942 --> 02:32:58,310
[SPEAKER_03]: is 5.0 where the next one runner up is air to water source heat pump, right about 4.0 plus minus.

828
02:32:58,991 --> 02:33:00,813
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's what's out there.

829
02:33:00,833 --> 02:33:07,820
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not just like it's a trend, but it's what's more efficient and more feasible in terms of installation, familiarity.

830
02:33:08,800 --> 02:33:15,922
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, there could be technology that could live somewhere else, but the challenges with that would be, like, for example, I'll give you an example.

831
02:33:16,122 --> 02:33:20,284
[SPEAKER_03]: There is an air to water source heat pump that is a CO2 driven.

832
02:33:20,864 --> 02:33:25,885
[SPEAKER_03]: So instead of using inside the equipment, using the A2L refrigerants, they use CO2.

833
02:33:27,306 --> 02:33:29,986
[SPEAKER_03]: They're highly efficient, especially in winter months.

834
02:33:30,367 --> 02:33:33,427
[SPEAKER_03]: Down to negative 22 degrees, they can give you 180 degree water.

835
02:33:33,888 --> 02:33:35,088
[SPEAKER_03]: However, they're proprietary.

836
02:33:35,762 --> 02:33:40,143
[SPEAKER_03]: So for public projects, they may not be an option unless we can flat spec it.

837
02:33:40,483 --> 02:33:44,684
[SPEAKER_03]: And another part of that is that they're very expensive because of that fact.

838
02:33:45,624 --> 02:33:53,166
[SPEAKER_03]: Where, for example, you can purchase an air to water heat pump for $2,000 a ton, you're going to pay $6,000 a ton.

839
02:33:54,326 --> 02:34:01,248
[SPEAKER_03]: The other challenge with that is when you have anything that breaks, replacement costs, you know, it's all factored in.

840
02:34:01,668 --> 02:34:02,969
[SPEAKER_03]: So it could be very costly.

841
02:34:03,229 --> 02:34:04,709
[SPEAKER_03]: So currently, geothermal,

842
02:34:06,258 --> 02:34:10,480
[SPEAKER_03]: Number one, air to water two, and then traditional VRF number three.

843
02:34:10,800 --> 02:34:15,062
[SPEAKER_03]: That's what's, I don't even think there is a fourth option.

844
02:34:15,302 --> 02:34:18,824
[SPEAKER_03]: There's hybrid options that you can combine any of these combinations.

845
02:34:20,164 --> 02:34:33,410
[SPEAKER_03]: Someone could ask the questions like, well, all electric is an electric option, but the problem with that is the efficiency, although compared to fossil fuel systems, is greater, but compared to air to water source heat pumps, it's kind of like pretty bad.

846
02:34:34,158 --> 02:34:40,080
[SPEAKER_03]: It's you put in one unit, you get one unit out, whereas geothermal, you put one in, you take five units out.

847
02:34:40,221 --> 02:34:42,041
[SPEAKER_03]: So it's kind of a no-brainer there.

848
02:34:42,361 --> 02:34:43,542
[SPEAKER_03]: Does that answer your question?

849
02:34:43,562 --> 02:34:43,882
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, absolutely.

