864
02:35:55,978 --> 02:35:58,940
[SPEAKER_20]: Like during the life cycle of the equipment if that makes sense.

865
02:35:58,980 --> 02:36:15,771
[SPEAKER_20]: I know that some people may have questions I know that I do obviously that's why I'm asking about what may happen if at some point later down the line the existing systems have to be then you know the Damage to them or just like the life cycle them have concluded and how that may impact the new the new systems.

866
02:36:15,791 --> 02:36:15,811
[SPEAKER_20]: I

867
02:36:16,361 --> 02:36:23,043
[SPEAKER_22]: So we wouldn't want to keep the existing boilers because they're essentially at the end of their useful life.

868
02:36:23,143 --> 02:36:24,684
[SPEAKER_22]: So we would be replacing them.

869
02:36:25,444 --> 02:36:38,849
[SPEAKER_22]: And again, if we do choose option one, the team has to work through how do we manage recovery or what do you call it, build preservation heat, you know, in a power outage, you know, what do we want to do?

870
02:36:38,909 --> 02:36:44,251
[SPEAKER_22]: Do we want electric boilers that are powered from a diesel fire generator or do we want,

871
02:36:45,082 --> 02:36:50,344
[SPEAKER_22]: gas fire boilers, you know, that we would do like newer technology condensing boilers for that option.

872
02:36:50,384 --> 02:36:52,605
[SPEAKER_22]: But that's something we have to work through.

873
02:36:52,725 --> 02:36:57,367
[SPEAKER_22]: But in terms of when we're done, whatever option

874
02:36:58,102 --> 02:37:00,644
[SPEAKER_22]: it will match sort of the life cycle of everything else.

875
02:37:01,044 --> 02:37:02,905
[SPEAKER_22]: There won't be a difference there.

876
02:37:03,986 --> 02:37:05,587
[SPEAKER_22]: I hope that answered your question.

877
02:37:05,607 --> 02:37:06,107
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you very much.

878
02:37:06,408 --> 02:37:08,209
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I ask you a follow-up question?

879
02:37:08,229 --> 02:37:08,489
[SPEAKER_03]: Sure.

880
02:37:08,509 --> 02:37:26,361
[SPEAKER_03]: Just for our knowledge, different districts in Massachusetts have different expectations, and what we're finding is that a lot of places, when the conversation is about preservation heat, they often say that we hear you, we think that's a good thought, but we don't really use power for an extended amount of time.

881
02:37:27,238 --> 02:37:31,522
[SPEAKER_03]: And often many towns around here, that is true, right?

882
02:37:31,542 --> 02:37:34,605
[SPEAKER_03]: They don't lose power for more than a few hours at a time.

883
02:37:35,166 --> 02:37:38,850
[SPEAKER_03]: And so what is the expectation or experience here in this town?

884
02:37:40,071 --> 02:37:42,974
[SPEAKER_20]: That might be a superintendent.

885
02:37:45,430 --> 02:37:46,851
[SPEAKER_09]: I would probably have to concur.

886
02:37:48,472 --> 02:37:54,256
[SPEAKER_09]: There have not been many opportunities, especially at the schools that we are talking about.

887
02:37:54,276 --> 02:38:00,421
[SPEAKER_09]: The one that was from 1970 is a different story, and we are actively trying to work on that.

888
02:38:00,481 --> 02:38:07,265
[SPEAKER_09]: But for our K to 8 buildings, that has not been a concern or an issue.

889
02:38:07,405 --> 02:38:09,527
[SPEAKER_03]: The power grid is OK is what I'm thinking.

890
02:38:10,547 --> 02:38:20,791
[SPEAKER_17]: We can get outage history, and this often comes up when we need reliable sources of power for things like fire pumps in the building.

891
02:38:22,031 --> 02:38:26,253
[SPEAKER_17]: If you don't have a generator, you have to prove that it's a reliable power source.

892
02:38:26,693 --> 02:38:31,615
[SPEAKER_17]: So that information is available and we can look at that, but I would say, and I live locally,

893
02:38:32,563 --> 02:38:36,865
[SPEAKER_17]: Generally, outages are not extensive enough that you have to worry about.

894
02:38:37,466 --> 02:38:49,312
[SPEAKER_17]: When we say preservation heat, it's not to preserve the kids in the class, because if there's an event that's causing an outage, it's probably not school, but you don't want the pipes freezing, essentially.

895
02:38:50,193 --> 02:39:02,159
[SPEAKER_17]: Whereas, you don't have to get too far outside of the Boston metro region where the grid is not as reliable, and this is a serious consideration.

896
02:39:04,045 --> 02:39:04,365
[SPEAKER_10]: Makes sense.

897
02:39:04,385 --> 02:39:04,705
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

898
